// GAP (open 2026-07-22): `orelse` inside a && / || RHS of a PLAIN ASSIGNMENT
// statement is eagerly evaluated (short-circuit violated). A plain `x = <expr>`
// goes to lower_expr's passthrough (NODE_ASSIGN op==TOK_EQ), which hands the RHS
// to pre_lower_orelse (hoists the orelse BEFORE the &&) instead of
// lower_shortcircuit_to_dest. side_count becomes 1 (ping ran) though `a` is
// false. The var-decl form `bool x = a && (ping() orelse false);` is correct.
// Silent miscompile; a trap inside the orelse source would also fire spuriously.
u32 side_count;
?bool ping() { side_count += 1; return true; }
u32 main() {
    bool a = false;
    bool x = false;
    x = a && (ping() orelse false);   // passthrough — orelse eagerly evaluated
    return side_count;                 // expected 0; actual 1
}
